g.text: DOCKER
What's docker?
It's a way to package an application and
all the necessary dependencies and configuration
files. In this way, sharing an application
become easier and its deployment could
be more effective.
Where do containers live?
There are special repos in which docker images
can manage stored; they could be private
or public, like the DuckerHub.
Why could docker improve the applications development?
Before the birth of docker, developers must share the same
environment trying to exactly reproduce it, even if the OS'
were different. The installation of all the dependecies
could be very tedious, especially because the OS' could be different.
The deployment procedure show the same issues.
Containers have their own isolation OS layer plus the application
and the dependencies: everything is packed into an isolation
environment. Moreover, the commands to install and use the
docker are the same.

TECHNICAL
FEATURES
From a technical point of view, what's docker?
A docker is made up of layers of images.
An image is an exact replica of the contents
of a storage device.
So, the first layer is the linux base image
and then, in order to reach the application image,
multiple layers are added.
Virtual machine vs. Container
First of all, every computer is made up of an hardware,
a OS kernel and applications. As of Linux, there are a
lot of kernel distributions because the applications
change but not the kernel.
Both the virtual machine and docker exploit virtualization
but, what is the virtualized part of the OS?
Docker virtualizes the app layer and uses the kernel of
the host! On the other hand, the virtual machine virtualises
the application layer and the kernel.
So, as a consequence, docker are much more smaller and
faster than the VM. VMs can be ran on top of every
hardware, while containers must be compatible with your OS.
So, let's have a window kernel OS with its applications and
a linux-based container: it could be come incompatibility.
This is true also for the older Mac versions and windows older
than 10. In order to create compatibility between
these things, a Docker toolbox makes it possible for the
host to run different docker images creating a king of bridge.

BASIC COMMANDS
Docker image vs. Docker container
The former consists in the actual package, i.e. the
not running application, while the latter one
consists in the running application on a local
environment. So, the container is the running
environment for the Image. For example, the
application could be mongo or redis, while the
container is made up of the virtual filesystem,
the app image and env configs.
So, Dockerhub contains only images!
Commands:
1. docker pull name_image
Download a docker image from the docker hub.
At the first iteration, all layers are downloaded;
then, only the differences are fetched.
2. docker images
Check the local available images. They have versions
defined by the tag field. At this point, no app
is running, so no containers occur.
3. docker run -d -phost_post:cont_port name_image
--name name_new_image name_image
Pull and run the docker image -> docker container.
-d: runs the image in detached mode (because
otherwise a prompt must be kept open).
-p: it allows to specify the port of the host's
connected to the container's port. In this way,
it's possible to attach to different containers
the same port which listen to different host's port.
--name: create a new container starting from an available
image.
4. docker ps -a
List of the running containers.
For each container, the id, image and port are written.
The port specifies on which the port the container
is listening for the upcoming requests. If there is a
conflict, the port os the container could be the same
but the port form the host must differ.
-a: shows the running and not running containers.
It's useful if you want to run again a stopped
container whose ID isnt show anymore into
docker ps.
5. docker stop id_container
It stops the run of a container through its ID.
6. docker start id_container
It starts the run of a container through its ID.
7. docker logs id_container
Print the logs of the specified container.
8. docker exec -it container_id /bin/bash
As the root user, you enter the container file system
and use it.
Since docker containers are independent from each other,
two version of the same app could run without conflicts.
DEPLOY A CONTAINER

MongoDB pulled out from docker hub.
Now, the app is ready and the deploy phase is ready
to occur. Commit your project on git. Then, jekins builds

Finally, the repo will be pushed into the server
